title: A Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Study of the Safety and Pharmacokinetics of MK-1942 Administered to Alzheimer's Disease Patients Receiving Donepezil Treatment.
description_brief: The study investigated the effects on safety and pharmacokinetics (PK) of MK-1942 and donepezil when co-administered to participants with Alzheimer's Disease with mild-to-moderate cognitive impairment stably treated with donepezil. The objectives of this study were to determine if the combination of MK-1942 with donepezil increases the incidence or severity of adverse events (AEs) previously reported for these agents alone, or results in unanticipated AEs in the patient population targeted for MK-1942 treatment. In addition, changes in the PK parameters of either MK-1942 or donepezil as a result of co-administration were assessed.

outcomeMeasures.description: The number of participants with abnormal (impaired) results on targeted neurological exams will be presented. The targeted neurological exam contains Modules 1, 2 and 5 of the general examination, focusing on arousal, cranial nerve function, and gait and will be administered several times throughout the treatment period starting on Day 1 up until Day 29. The number of participants with abnormal (impaired) results on targeted neurological exams will be reported. Each exam will be graded as Normal or Impaired with the abnormality described.

outcomeMeasures.title: Number of Participants Who Reported Suicidal Ideation and/or Behavior on Study Based on Responses to the Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale (C-SSRS)
outcomeMeasures.description: The number of participants with suicidality using the C-SSRS is presented. The C-SSR will be used in this study only for the purpose of safety monitoring by measuring the incidence of different types of suicidality categories during treatment. C-SSRS assessment will be based upon a clinician's interpretation of the participant's responses to the C-SSRS questions, not by a numbered scale. Suicidal ideation and/or behaviors identified on the C-SSRS may not be considered an adverse event, based on the investigator's judgment. Participants who report at least one occurrence of suicidal behavior or suicidal ideation will be counted as having experienced suicidality. Suicidal behavior includes suicide attempt, aborted attempt, interrupted attempt, or preparatory behavior. Suicidal ideation include a wish to die or active suicidal thought with or without method, intent or plan.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests MK-1942 co‑administered with donepezil in people with mild‑to‑moderate Alzheimer’s disease to assess safety and pharmacokinetics; the program description and trial listing identify MK-1942 as a small‑molecule investigational drug (target not disclosed). citeturn0search1turn0search0

Act: Key facts extracted — MK-1942 is a Merck small molecule; the cited Phase 1 trial (NCT04308304) evaluated safety/PK of MK-1942 given with donepezil in 27 AD patients. Later Phase 2 plans used ADAS‑Cog as a primary outcome, indicating an intent to measure symptomatic cognitive benefit. citeturn0search1turn0search7turn0search0

Ambiguity noted: The molecular target of MK-1942 was not disclosed in public sources, so it cannot be confidently classified as a small molecule that specifically targets AD pathology (e.g., amyloid or tau). ALZFORUM and trial registries list it as a small molecule with an unknown target. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Reflect: Given (a) MK-1942 is a small molecule with unknown molecular target and (b) the development program included symptomatic cognitive endpoints (ADAS‑Cog) and add‑on use with donepezil, the most appropriate category is 'cognitive enhancer' (drug intended to improve cognitive function symptomatically rather than a biologic or clearly pathology‑targeted disease‑modifying agent). If later evidence showed MK-1942 specifically targets amyloid, tau, or another disease pathway, the classification should be revised to 'disease-targeted small molecule'. citeturn0search0turn0search1

explanation_agent: Reason: The trial tests MK-1942 (a Merck small-molecule investigational drug) co‑administered with donepezil to assess safety and pharmacokinetics in people with mild‑to‑moderate AD, but public sources list MK-1942's molecular target as undisclosed — therefore the mechanism cannot be mapped to a specific CADRO biology category. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Act: Key extracted facts — MK-1942 is a Merck small molecule; the Phase 1 interaction/safety/PK study (NCT04308304) enrolled 27 AD participants on stable donepezil and tested escalating MK-1942 doses vs placebo. Subsequent development plans included a Phase 2 adjunct study (ADAS‑Cog as an efficacy endpoint) before the program was later discontinued. These facts come from clinical-trial registries and ALZFORUM. citeturn0search1turn0search0turn0search4

Ambiguity noted: Multiple authoritative sources explicitly state MK-1942's target/mechanism was not disclosed publicly (so it cannot confidently be classified under CADRO categories like Amyloid, Tau, Neurotransmitter Receptors, etc.). Because the investigational molecule's target is unknown, assigning a pathology- or pathway-specific CADRO class would be speculative. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Reflect: Given the absence of a disclosed molecular target and that the development program treated MK-1942 as a symptomatic adjunct (cognitive-enhancer orientation) rather than a clearly disease-modifying agent, the most appropriate CADRO classification for this trial is S) Unknown Target. If Merck or other sources later disclose a defined biological target or pathway for MK-1942, the classification should be revisited and changed to the specific CADRO category that matches that target. citeturn0search0turn0search1
